---
/**
 * Why this matters — single dense block, two breakout concepts.
 *
 * Replaced the four-item roman-numeral list with one editorial
 * paragraph that opens the case, plus two breakout call-outs. Reads
 * as a magazine column, not a feature checklist.
 */
import '../styles/why.css';
---
<section class="why" id="how">
  <div class="why-inner">
    <div class="why-col">
      <p class="why-stamp">Why an impact study at all</p>
      <p class="why-lede">
        Most of what a government, a tribal council, or a board cares about &mdash; <em>can we keep this clinic open, will the bond pass, what happens if the federal program disappears</em> &mdash; lives downstream of one number. An economic impact study is the work of finding that number, and the assumption ledger behind it, before the question gets asked.
      </p>
      <p class="why-body">
        Without one, the conversation is in raw payroll and the loudest voice wins. With one, it&rsquo;s in jobs, output, and earnings &mdash; and a council member can quote the line with a source attached. The platforms aren&rsquo;t there to replace a consultant&rsquo;s judgment. They&rsquo;re there to make the consultant&rsquo;s judgment auditable, cheaper, and rerunnable when the council agenda changes next month.
      </p>
    </div>

    <aside class="why-aside">
      <div class="why-card">
        <p class="why-card__head">A budget conversation becomes an investment conversation.</p>
        <p class="why-card__body">A water-system bond stops being a $9M expense and starts being $9M of direct payroll, supplier work, and household wages across the county. The case changes shape.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="why-card why-card--alt">
        <p class="why-card__head">A scenario before a commitment.</p>
        <p class="why-card__body">Cut a program, add twenty positions, expand operations, change a policy &mdash; model the second-order consequences with the assumption ledger attached, before the council votes.</p>
      </div>
    </aside>
  </div>
</section>
